history.content: Pre-reqs are generally not enforced except for in extreme cases like a semester or two ago, when they unexpectedly had to downsize the class (after people had enrolled). Personally I'm enrolled in 189 currently but have not taken Math 53, as at least one example of pre-reqs being un-enforced (at enrollment time).

children.subject: I strongly suggest you to take 53 before 189. The class is heavy on multivariate calculus, even with Shewchuck.
Thanks for pointing out that 126 qualifies; I'll add it to the web page.

Pre-reqs for this semester's version of 189 (from shewchuk's site):

  • Math 53 (or another vector calculus course),
  • Math 54, Math 110, or EE 16A+16B (or another linear algebra course),
  • CS 70 or Stat 134 (or another probability course). [EE126 qualifies]

As somebody in the class now, if you lack these knowledge areas then it will not be easy to catch up unless you are a superstar student. Also you may get less out of the class because you are spending more time learning the pre-req material rather than the course content. Just take the pre-reqs and don't bother with this problem.

Prerequisites aren't directly enforced.  But students who don't have a good intuitive grasp of linear algebra, probability, and gradients tend to wash out of the class.  (This probably includes a few students who did take those classes but didn't really get them.)  Don't worry about what courses you've taken; worry about what you understand.

BTW, 16A and 16B have been updated in a way that provides a solid dollop of what's needed for 189.
